{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Hematoxylin and eosin (H&E) stained tissue sections are the mainstay of cancer diagnosis and many treatment decisions.",
    "Their ubiquitousness makes them the single largest source of data for studying the highly heterogeneous phenotype of tumors, yielding information from subcellular resolution to tissue architecture and complex interactions within the tumor microenvironment [1] [2] [3].",
    "However, pathologist interpretation is time-consuming and prone to inter-observer variation, depending on expertise, knowledge, and on the inherent difficulty in characterizing certain tumors or patterns [4] [5] [6] [7].",
    "Supervised deep learning methods have shown to be on par with specialists on tumor classification tasks [8] [9] [10].",
    "In addition, these approaches have also been employed to tackle more challenging questions, such as predicting genetic alterations 8, 11, 12, survival [13] [14] [15] and immunotherapy response 16."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
